These four HCoV communities have entirely adapted to humans and generally have a small likelihood of mutating into highly pathogenic diseases. Nevertheless, exceptional cases have occurred for unknown reasons, such as in the case of the more virulent subtype HCoV-NL63, which has recently been to cause severe lower respiratory tract infections in China.
Generally, when the ability to move efficiently and continue to defend itself in humans is obtained, the virulence and pathogenicity of this HCoV is also reduced.
